                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d499">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A 4e 1/51: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurmcm</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-03-18T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 18, 1924—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>55. Your No. 77 March 13, 4 p.m. and Evans’ telegram to Buforcom March 15.<note
                        n="32" xml:id="d499fn32">Telegram from Mr. Arthur H. Evans, assistant
                        commercial attaché at Peking, to the Bureau of Foreign and Domestic
                        Commerce; not printed.</note> Pending the receipt of further instructions,
                    you should not take such a part in conference with your colleagues as to
                    indicate or commit in any way the position of this Government with respect to
                    the proposal for a preliminary conference.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
